    Maize South High School graduate gets private ceremony after testing positive for COVID-19

    Thursday, July 1st 2021, 4:27 PM EDT
    written by KAKE News
    Piper Pennetti holding her diploma. (Twitter/@maize266)

    MAIZE, Kan. (KAKE) - A Maize South High School graduate was just two days away from walking across the stage when she got the news. The school district stepped in and gave her a ceremony she will never forget. 

    When Piper Pennetti first heard she tested positive for COVID-19 she was mad and then cried, the school district said on its website. After she spoke with her high school counselor, she concluded her college graduate would be much more special.

    "I felt better knowing I wasn't missing out on both of my graduations and that I'd get to still wear my cap and gown one day down the road," Pennetti said. 

    A few days after graduation, and when Pennetti was out of quarantine, Maize South principal David Hickerson invited her to her own private ceremony. Hickerson, USD 266 superintendent Dr. Chad Higgins and three board of education members presented Pennetti her diploma. 

    "At first, I was surprised. I knew I would have to get my diploma, but I figured they would mail it to me," Pennetti said.

    Pennetti said she was excited that the district wanted to give her this experience. She was able to wear her graduation gown and her mom was even able to snap some photos. 

    "I will never forget this and how they tried to make it special for me," Pennetti said. 

    Pennetti plans to attend Wichita State in the fall and major in journalism.
